<h4>Q: Distance, Figure and Time Scales?</h4>

<b><u>Figure Scales:</u></b>
<p>This is an element based game, where combat units are made up of a number of elements (or bases).</p>
<p>The basic manouevre element of the game is the Brigade, which is made up several bases of close order Infantry. A typical Infantry Brigade at combat strength will have between 4-8 bases of close order Infantry, and a Brigade Commander base.<p>
<p>A base of Line Infantry in close order represents a half-battalion (roughly 150 man frontage, in 2 or 3 ranks). The frontage of this half-battalion element therefore defines the ground scale of 100 paces for every aspect of the game from here on.  100 paces == 1 base width.</p>

<b><u>Ground Scale:</u></b>
<p>As defined by the basing system, each base of close order Infantry = 100 paces.</p>
<p>The critical distance in the game is the "quarter mile" or roughly 500 paces. A "quarter mile" has the following special characteristics:</p>
<ul>
	<li>It is the maximum range of the best small arms fire, and cannister fire from guns.</li>
	<li>It is the distance that Infantry can advance in a 5 minute period.</li>
	<li>Opposing Infantry units within this distance of each other are considered to be engaged and under shot of each other. This affects command control, morale state, the ability to change formation, or receive new orders.<li>
	<li>It is the maximum distance that Cavalry can charge, without the defender having time to react.</li>
	<li>It is the maximum distance that supporting units can offer effective support and shelter to other units.</li>
	<li>It is the maximum distance that a commander can control a sub-unit, or assess its condition.</li>
	<li>Cavalry moves are in neat multiples of quarter miles.</li>
	<li>Artillery range bands are in neat multiples of quarter miles.</li>
	<li>At half this critical distance:
		<ul>
			<li>Maximum effective range of musket volleys.</li>
			<li>Supporting lines offer guaranteed shelter for supported units.</li>
			<li>Opposing units this close to each other are considered locked in to the engagement.</li>
			<li>Supporting units take bouncethrough damage from incoming artilley when this close to the target unit.</li>
		</ul>
	</li>	
	<li>At a quarter of this critical distance:
		<ul>
			<li>Musket fire effect is doubled.</li>
			<li>Supporting units within this distance count towards melee results.</li>
			<li>Supporting units within this distance take damage from cannister and musket fire at the target unit.</li>
			<li>Opposing units this close to each other can no longer receive new orders, or change formation.</li>
		</ul>
	</li>

</ul>
<p>Consider the tabletop to be divided into a grid of "quarter mile" sections.</p>
<p>To calculate the "quarter mile" scale for your tabletop, measure out the frontage of 5 close order infantry bases ... round it off to the nearest nice even number, and then declare that to be your base distance. You can now create a measuring stick marked off in quarter mile increments. On the end of the measuring stick, you can divide the last section into a half-"quarter mile", and a</p>
<p>For example: Lets say we are using infantry bases with a 40mm max frontage .. 5 x 40mm = 200mm, which gives us a quarter mile of 8 inches.  For 60mm max frontage, that gives a quarter mile of 12 inches.</p>

<b><u>Time Scale:</u></b>
<p>Based on the above, the game is divided into 5 minute time slices, which gives enough time for :</p>
<ul>
	<li>A commander to draft a new set of orders.</li>
	<li>A sub-commander to receive and begin to act on new orders.</li>
	<li>A typical close combat action to reach a conclusion.</li>
	<li>A typical fresh musket volley to turn into a smoke filled firefight.</li>
	<li>An artillery battery to limber or unlimber.</li>
	<li>A brigade sized unit to perform a significant change of formation or facing.</li>
</ul>


