<h4>Q: Command, Control, Turn Sequence?</h4>
<p>The Game Turn Sequence is as follows :</p>
<ol>
	<li>Initial Game Setup, deployment and orders.</li>
	<li>General Movement (simultaneous for all players)</li>
	<li>Resolve ranged artilley fire<li>
	<li>Submit New Orders</li>
	<li>Tactical Actions (in parallel for all individual close engagements)
	<ul>
		<li>For each tactical engagement, determine which units are attacking who.</li>
		<li>Resolve the combat.</li>
	</ul>
	<li>Leader emergency actions.</li>
	<li>Once all tactical actions are resolved, go to step 2.</li>
	</li>
</ol>

<p>Each Player's forces are divided into a heirachy of commands, from Corps Commander -» Division Commander -» Brigade Commander.</p>
<p>At the start of each Game, the tabletop is logically divided into sectors such as Left Flank / Centre / Right Flank, and in each sector, one or more objective points are defined and agreed upon by the players. These can be roads, a town, a bridge, some woods, a mountain pass, etc.</p>
<p>At the start of each Game, each player must decide for each unit which logical sector they start in, and what their initial deployment state is.</p>
<p>At the start of each Game, each player must issue each sub-command with both an Objective, and an Order. The intial Objective must be one of the objective points defined above. The Order can be one of :</p>
<ul>
	<li>Attack: Advance on the objective, and take it by force.</li>
	<li>Defend: Take position on the objective and hold it against all oncomers.</li>
	<li>Support: Objective = specified unit, and specified flank or rear of that unit.<li>
	<li>Reserve: Maintain readiness to accept new orders, otherwise keep out of the way.</li>
</ul>
<p>Depending on the Player's Rank, additional type of orders may be used in the Game, including:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Probe: Seek out, engage and harrass the enemy in order to pin them in place.</li>
	<li>Advanced Guard: Proceed forward ahead of the main army to scout out the enemy, and harrass them as they deploy.</li>
	<li>Flank March: As it says.</li>
	<li></li>
</ul>

<p>During the Game, the Computer Umpire will consider the orders, engagement, control and morale state of every unit on the board, and compute what each unit decides to do next. The Computer then provides each Player with a list of all the moves that their units MUST make this next turn, where they are headed, and how far at a minimum they have to move.</p>

<p>All moves are performed simultaneously by all players in accordance with the istructions from the Computer. Moves are cut short however when opposing units close to within a "quarter mile" distance of each other.</p>

<p>At this point, Players may write up new orders for any sub-unit. This includes :</p>
<ul>
	<li>Change of Orders: ie - from Defend to Attack</li>
	<li>Change of Objective: Can specify a different objective, OR may now specify an enemy unit as the objective.</li>
	<li>Change of Formation: Can specify a different Brigade level formation, such a "Refuse Left Flank", or "Adopt Checkerboard of Attack Columns"</li>
</ul>

<p>After the orders are submitted, it will take 1 movement turn to dispatch the order, and then 1 movement turn for the sub-commander to enact the order.</p>



