<h4>Q: Troop Grades?</h4>
<p>The original Kriegsspeil rules do make a distinction between differences in the quality of opposing units in the odds calculation, but they don't make an attempt to quantify this over and above umpire discretion.</p>
<p>For this system, we need to apply some method of quantifying the difference for the computer to be able to crunch some numbers, so I have decided to stick with the familiar (and excessively detailed) troop grades from "Empire", which do a great job of providing granularity, determining training level and formation capabilites as well as simply morale  ... and add period flavour to any OOB.<p>
<p>This includes:</p>
<ol>
	<li>Guard</li>
	<li>Grenadier</li>
	<li>Elite</li>
	<li>Crack Line</li>
	<li>Regular Line</li>
	<li>2nd Rate / Reserve</li>
	<li>Conscript</li>
	<li>Landwehr</li>
	<li>Militia</li>
	<li>Rabble</li>
	<li>Angry Mob</li>
</ol>

<p>Artillery are graded as:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Heavy / 12lb</li>
	<li>Field / 9lb</li>
	<li>Field / 6-8lb</li>
	<li>Light / Bn Guns 3-4lb</li>
	<li>Horse Guns</li>
	<li>Howitzers</li>
</ul>

<p>Cavalry units are graded with the above Morale Level, and have additional attributes including:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Heavy Battle Cavalry (Cuirassiers, Heavy Dragoons, etc)</li>
	<li>Light Battle Cavalry (Hussars / Mamelukes, etc)</li>
	<li>Lancers</li>
	<li>Dragoons</li>
	<li>Light Cavalry (Chasseurs, Mtd Jagers)</li>
	<li>Cossacks / other Irregular Cavalry</li>
	<li>Dubious Cavalry (Hastily assembled Landwehr or National Guard cav)</li>
</ul>

